  "texts": [
    "In our notations this means that P Correct (q, a; M, T ≥ 0) = 0.",
    "Alternatively, if P Correct (q, a; M, T ≥ 0) > 0, i.e.",
    "M sometimes predicts the correct answer to q, we consider (q, a) as Known.",
    "In this choice, we posit that if prompting M to answer q can sometimes result with the cor- rect answer a, then M must have some association with the relevant fact.",
    "Recognizing that knowledge can vary in degrees of certainty and extent, we divide the Known (q, a) pairs into three distinct categories (top three rows in Tables 2a and 2b)."
  ],
